249
00:10:21,300 --> 00:10:24,100
multiplying eight different
sets of numbers together,

250
00:10:24,100 --> 00:10:26,100
I can run each of
those in parallel

251
00:10:26,100 --> 00:10:28,860
and then summarize the
results at the end.

252
00:10:28,860 --> 00:10:30,010
That's good.

253
00:10:30,010 --> 00:10:31,830
And a multiplication
operation is

254
00:10:31,830 --> 00:10:34,510
so fast that would feel
like light speed anyways.

255
00:10:34,510 --> 00:10:36,780
But if it's a complex
task, it might actually

256
00:10:36,780 --> 00:10:40,150
be something where I'm a
little bit bottlenecked.

257
00:10:40,150 --> 00:10:43,600
These processes take a while,
and I can only do eight of them,

258
00:10:43,600 --> 00:10:45,490
eight operations in parallel.

259
00:10:45,490 --> 00:10:47,830
Well, something
like a GPU or TPU,

260
00:10:47,830 --> 00:10:50,420
which is a very specific
chip designed by Google,

261
00:10:50,420 --> 00:10:52,010
it's called a tensor
processing unit,

262
00:10:52,010 --> 00:10:54,230
but it roughly runs
on the same idea,

263
00:10:54,230 --> 00:10:57,310
these are designed to have
thousands, tens of thousands

264
00:10:57,310 --> 00:10:58,570
of cores.

265
00:10:58,570 --> 00:11:01,100
They're not as general
purpose, of course,

266
00:11:01,100 --> 00:11:03,230
where a CPU can open
up a Word document,

267
00:11:03,230 --> 00:11:04,970
edit it and do all
these sorts of things,

268
00:11:04,970 --> 00:11:07,090
a GPU certainly
can't do that, but it

269
00:11:07,090 --> 00:11:10,540
can do very quick mathematical
operations, a multiplication

270
00:11:10,540 --> 00:11:11,620
step.

271
00:11:11,620 --> 00:11:13,210
And this actually
comes from the fact

272
00:11:13,210 --> 00:11:17,410
that graphics, in video
games, are inherently

273
00:11:17,410 --> 00:11:19,610
a bunch of little
multiplication operations.

274
00:11:19,610 --> 00:11:21,490
So when we started to
move towards things

275
00:11:21,490 --> 00:11:25,120
like neural networks and machine
learning, which themselves are

276
00:11:25,120 --> 00:11:28,120
also a bunch of little
multiplication operations,

277
00:11:28,120 --> 00:11:30,850
researchers realized that we
could leverage these GPUs down

278
00:11:30,850 --> 00:11:32,240
to dramatically accelerate it.

279
00:11:32,240 --> 00:11:34,090
If I need to do--

280
00:11:34,090 --> 00:11:36,560
take something like a ChatGPT.

281
00:11:36,560 --> 00:11:39,500
Those have trillions
of parameters.

282
00:11:39,500 --> 00:11:41,200
Each of those
parameters needing to be

283
00:11:41,200 --> 00:11:43,810
multiplied by other
numbers as we're

284
00:11:43,810 --> 00:11:45,380
trying to make predictions.

285
00:11:45,380 --> 00:11:48,040
Well, if I have
eight cores, then

286
00:11:48,040 --> 00:11:51,550
I can only do eight operations
in parallel or eight

287
00:11:51,550 --> 00:11:54,100
of those trillions of
operations in parallel,

288
00:11:54,100 --> 00:11:56,650
versus if I have something
like a GPU or TPU,

289
00:11:56,650 --> 00:12:00,370
I can really dramatically
speed up the compute here.

290
00:12:00,370 --> 00:12:02,890
Now, the important detail
in the context of the Cloud

291
00:12:02,890 --> 00:12:09,698
is that if I were to do
this on, let's say, a GPU

292
00:12:09,698 --> 00:12:10,990
that I had here at home, right.

293
00:12:10,990 --> 00:12:14,180
I have a GPU in my computer.

294
00:12:14,180 --> 00:12:16,220
I'd be a little limited.

295
00:12:16,220 --> 00:12:19,940
A big 4090 GPU is probably
the largest consumer GPU

296
00:12:19,940 --> 00:12:21,650
as of this recording.

297
00:12:21,650 --> 00:12:24,780
That is going to cost you
somewhere around $2,000,

298
00:12:24,780 --> 00:12:27,540
maybe $1,500 to $2,000.

299
00:12:27,540 --> 00:12:30,390
And I might have a process,
again, something like a ChatGPT,

300
00:12:30,390 --> 00:12:32,340
trying to train a
model like ChatGPT

301
00:12:32,340 --> 00:12:35,970
that might take hundreds,
thousands of GPUs

302
00:12:35,970 --> 00:12:39,670
to really meaningfully get
done in a short amount of time.

303
00:12:39,670 --> 00:12:41,380
And so now all of
a sudden, I mean,

304
00:12:41,380 --> 00:12:43,080
it's just
incomprehensibly expensive

305
00:12:43,080 --> 00:12:46,020
to purchase all those
resources, but I

306
00:12:46,020 --> 00:12:49,180
can leverage Cloud
resources to rent those,

307
00:12:49,180 --> 00:12:50,790
and we'll talk about
why that-- or how

308
00:12:50,790 --> 00:12:52,530
that works in a little bit.

309
00:12:52,530 --> 00:12:55,590
But to not drag on
this point too long,

310
00:12:55,590 --> 00:12:57,090
to briefly talk
about memory, which

311
00:12:57,090 --> 00:12:59,250
we'll spend a whole week on.

312
00:12:59,250 --> 00:13:02,460
There's two types of memory
we'll discuss in this class.

313
00:13:02,460 --> 00:13:04,210
One of those is kind
of volatile memory,

314
00:13:04,210 --> 00:13:07,360
so RAM, you'll hear me refer
to as RAM almost always.

315
00:13:07,360 --> 00:13:09,490
And the other is
non-volatile memory,

316
00:13:09,490 --> 00:13:12,330
and that'll be your hard drive
or your solid state drive.

317
00:13:12,330 --> 00:13:14,940
RAM, think about that as
the working memory, that

318
00:13:14,940 --> 00:13:20,430
is how much kind of
information I can hold,

319
00:13:20,430 --> 00:13:24,820
kind of readily available to
use or operate on right now.

320
00:13:24,820 --> 00:13:27,580
And when I shut my computer
off, that's going to disappear.

321
00:13:27,580 --> 00:13:29,220
It's not going to
be existing anymore.

322
00:13:29,220 --> 00:13:31,410
Versus my hard drive or
my solid state drive,

323
00:13:31,410 --> 00:13:33,250
that is my long term storage.

324
00:13:33,250 --> 00:13:35,627
So if I want to save
pictures on my hard drive,

325
00:13:35,627 --> 00:13:37,210
that's what we're
talking about there.

326
00:13:37,210 --> 00:13:40,200
So that's just designed to
hold it there and be really

327
00:13:40,200 --> 00:13:44,200
cheap and efficient to store a
lot of information, versus RAM.

328
00:13:44,200 --> 00:13:47,580
It's going to be more
expensive for equivalent

329
00:13:47,580 --> 00:13:51,430
volumes of memory, but it'll be
much, much faster as far as read

330
00:13:51,430 --> 00:13:55,000
and write speeds, and so I can
operate on it more quickly.

331
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:58,420
So anyway, that's all to say,
that is the core components

332
00:13:58,420 --> 00:14:00,820
of the computer we're
worried about in the context

333
00:14:00,820 --> 00:14:02,820
of this course.

334
00:14:02,820 --> 00:14:06,030
And then if you put all those
pieces together, put all those

335
00:14:06,030 --> 00:14:08,490
together into one
box, and then you

336
00:14:08,490 --> 00:14:10,490
can see here as
this rack shows, I

337
00:14:10,490 --> 00:14:12,270
can stack a bunch of
those boxes together

338
00:14:12,270 --> 00:14:15,150
and basically just connect a
bunch of computers together.

339
00:14:15,150 --> 00:14:19,840
And really, that is
fundamentally what a server is.

340
00:14:19,840 --> 00:14:22,200
So you might have heard
this term a server before.

341
00:14:22,200 --> 00:14:25,120
But even-- again, we
mentioned Netflix before.

342
00:14:25,120 --> 00:14:27,528
Netflix has to be
hosted somewhere.

343
00:14:27,528 --> 00:14:29,820
I have to have those videos
saved, some of those movies

344
00:14:29,820 --> 00:14:30,880
saved somewhere.

345
00:14:30,880 --> 00:14:33,600
I have to have the website,
the code of the website saved

346
00:14:33,600 --> 00:14:34,390
somewhere.

347
00:14:34,390 --> 00:14:36,000
And that's what a
server does for me,

348
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:38,790
is it allows me to basically
say, OK, well, this computer has

349
00:14:38,790 --> 00:14:39,970
the code for it.

350
00:14:39,970 --> 00:14:44,020
All of these servers, all
these racks within the server,

351
00:14:44,020 --> 00:14:45,760
they have all the videos.

352
00:14:45,760 --> 00:14:49,810
And so therefore, when somebody
comes to visit netflix.com,

353
00:14:49,810 --> 00:14:52,470
what they're actually doing is
sending a request to the server,

354
00:14:52,470 --> 00:14:55,740
and that server is sending
the relevant information back.

355
00:14:55,740 --> 00:14:57,720
So very, very useful.

356
00:14:57,720 --> 00:14:59,460
These are the types
of things that we'll

357
00:14:59,460 --> 00:15:03,620
use for gaming, for hosting
websites, hosting applications,

358
00:15:03,620 --> 00:15:06,100
storing data, whatever
that might be.

359
00:15:06,100 --> 00:15:09,980
A server is really just
a computer that is--

360
00:15:09,980 --> 00:15:12,130
or a bunch of computers
stacked together.

361
00:15:12,130 --> 00:15:15,920
So nothing crazier than that.

362
00:15:15,920 --> 00:15:19,070
And really what we can
have is, we can have--

363
00:15:19,070 --> 00:15:22,160
I mean, again, when I was at
Carvana, we had our own servers.

364
00:15:22,160 --> 00:15:23,970
Before we were even
leveraging the Cloud,

365
00:15:23,970 --> 00:15:25,860
we had a room
filled with servers,

366
00:15:25,860 --> 00:15:27,170
looked something like this.

367
00:15:27,170 --> 00:15:31,280
A bunch of blinking
boxes in a room.

368
00:15:31,280 --> 00:15:35,300
And we could reasonably serve
all the content on our website

369
00:15:35,300 --> 00:15:39,320
from those servers, but
there are some limitations.

370
00:15:39,320 --> 00:15:41,030
So let's look at
what that means.

371
00:15:41,030 --> 00:15:45,920
So again, as we said, take
our Netflix example here.

372
00:15:45,920 --> 00:15:48,650
Maybe we have another
season of Stranger Things.

373
00:15:48,650 --> 00:15:51,550
Let's say it's Stranger
Things season 6, 10, whatever

374
00:15:51,550 --> 00:15:54,680
we're at, at this point.

375
00:15:54,680 --> 00:15:57,430
That has to be-- that is
a video, that is a file.

376
00:15:57,430 --> 00:15:59,040
That has to be
uploaded somewhere.

377
00:15:59,040 --> 00:16:01,340
So let's say that gets
uploaded from the studio

378
00:16:01,340 --> 00:16:02,610
up to our server.

379
00:16:02,610 --> 00:16:04,550
So now it's sitting
on our server here.

380
00:16:04,550 --> 00:16:06,680
And then we're sitting
there on our couch

381
00:16:06,680 --> 00:16:08,370
and we want to watch that video.

382
00:16:08,370 --> 00:16:11,570
We send a request and that
request returns a response.

383
00:16:11,570 --> 00:16:14,660
That response is the video
itself for us to watch.

384
00:16:14,660 --> 00:16:16,430
Again, that is
fundamentally what it looks

385
00:16:16,430 --> 00:16:18,500
like to deploy an application.

386
00:16:18,500 --> 00:16:20,030
And in this context,
we're talking

387
00:16:20,030 --> 00:16:22,560
about doing this on premise.

388
00:16:22,560 --> 00:16:25,050
That word on premise
means the premise

389
00:16:25,050 --> 00:16:28,070
is being this location
that we're at here,

390
00:16:28,070 --> 00:16:30,990
and we're managing those
physical resources.

391
00:16:30,990 --> 00:16:32,610
So we've purchased
the computers,

392
00:16:32,610 --> 00:16:34,440
we've plugged them
into our outlets,

393
00:16:34,440 --> 00:16:37,560
we're paying for the power,
the cooling, all that stuff.

394
00:16:37,560 --> 00:16:40,350
That's what an on
premise deployment is.

395
00:16:40,350 --> 00:16:44,060
And you'll hear me
use that term a lot.

396
00:16:44,060 --> 00:16:45,680
Pros and cons to that.

397
00:16:45,680 --> 00:16:47,430
There are some really
good pros, actually,

398
00:16:47,430 --> 00:16:49,820
and there's a lot of discussion
around this right now

399
00:16:49,820 --> 00:16:52,070
in general, which we'll get
into later in the semester

400
00:16:52,070 --> 00:16:55,500
about the value of Cloud
computing or Cloud resources

401
00:16:55,500 --> 00:16:57,660
versus on premise resources.

402
00:16:57,660 --> 00:17:01,950
But one big value of them
is they're fixed costs.

403
00:17:01,950 --> 00:17:03,930
Once I've purchased
a server, I know--

404
00:17:03,930 --> 00:17:06,569
that cost me an amount of
money, and I'll put it there

405
00:17:06,569 --> 00:17:09,310
in my room and
outside of, again,

406
00:17:09,310 --> 00:17:14,842
ongoing energy costs or cooling
costs, the costs are fixed.

407
00:17:14,842 --> 00:17:17,300
I've spent the amount of money
and that's what it costs me.

408
00:17:17,300 --> 00:17:18,842
Things aren't going
to necessarily go

409
00:17:18,842 --> 00:17:23,210
up or down in a large swing,
so that could be valuable.

410
00:17:23,210 --> 00:17:25,109
They also can have
very low latency.

411
00:17:25,109 --> 00:17:27,170
So if my users,
let's say, again, I

412
00:17:27,170 --> 00:17:30,890
have a server at my company
that is there for my employees

413
00:17:30,890 --> 00:17:33,733
to leverage for whatever
their tasks are, well,

414
00:17:33,733 --> 00:17:35,400
if it's right around
the corner from us,

415
00:17:35,400 --> 00:17:37,500
we can run a hard
wire directly to it.

416
00:17:37,500 --> 00:17:40,310
That's going to be infinitely
faster than anything

417
00:17:40,310 --> 00:17:42,410
else we can do over the web.

418
00:17:42,410 --> 00:17:45,120
And that can really help out
from a security standpoint,

419
00:17:45,120 --> 00:17:49,530
if we, for example, have to
have very sensitive information.

420
00:17:49,530 --> 00:17:53,690
If I'm a bank account or anybody
that might be storing very, very

421
00:17:53,690 --> 00:17:56,510
sensitive information,
I can physically,

422
00:17:56,510 --> 00:17:58,850
or especially in the context
of national security,

423
00:17:58,850 --> 00:18:01,040
you'll see this a
lot, where servers

424
00:18:01,040 --> 00:18:04,460
will be housed in a room with
no physical connections anywhere

425
00:18:04,460 --> 00:18:05,720
outside of power, maybe.

426
00:18:05,720 --> 00:18:08,750
They're not going to be
connected via ethernet

427
00:18:08,750 --> 00:18:10,200
to any outside room.

428
00:18:10,200 --> 00:18:13,770
That means that even if your
entire company or organization

429
00:18:13,770 --> 00:18:16,470
is compromised, if there's
nothing physically connected

430
00:18:16,470 --> 00:18:18,450
there, there's an air gap.

431
00:18:18,450 --> 00:18:21,890
And so that can be a very
secure way to deploy resources.

432
00:18:21,890 --> 00:18:24,060
You don't have to move
sensitive information around.

433
00:18:24,060 --> 00:18:26,190
And again, even if there's
an internet outage,

434
00:18:26,190 --> 00:18:27,370
if it's over there
in the room, you

435
00:18:27,370 --> 00:18:29,040
can just go run over
and connect to it.

436
00:18:29,040 --> 00:18:31,430
So there's some values there.

437
00:18:31,430 --> 00:18:35,930
But again, that comes with
a bunch of associated cons.

438
00:18:35,930 --> 00:18:39,170
You do have to pay for energy
consumption, cooling resources.

439
00:18:39,170 --> 00:18:42,080
You do have to have
a physical space.

440
00:18:42,080 --> 00:18:44,120
And this is the really
big one, is that you

441
00:18:44,120 --> 00:18:46,050
need to size it appropriately.

442
00:18:46,050 --> 00:18:50,340
If you have constant variations
in your demand of resources,

443
00:18:50,340 --> 00:18:53,220
your website gets visited
a lot one week of the year,

444
00:18:53,220 --> 00:18:56,360
but then the rest of the
year, it's never used,

445
00:18:56,360 --> 00:18:59,300
you have to size it
for the largest amount

446
00:18:59,300 --> 00:19:03,830
of users that you'll expect, and
the rest of the time you're just

447
00:19:03,830 --> 00:19:08,540
paying for unused resources.

448
00:19:08,540 --> 00:19:12,170
You're at risk for power outages
or any sort of physical damage

449
00:19:12,170 --> 00:19:13,380
to the building.

450
00:19:13,380 --> 00:19:15,890
And again, you now
need to staff people

451
00:19:15,890 --> 00:19:18,650
to maintain, upgrade,
backup all the resources

452
00:19:18,650 --> 00:19:20,060
that you have on site.

453
00:19:20,060 --> 00:19:22,800
So pros and cons.

454
00:19:22,800 --> 00:19:25,260
And that's what really
brings us to Cloud computing,

455
00:19:25,260 --> 00:19:27,960
is Cloud computing
says, well, what

456
00:19:27,960 --> 00:19:30,710
if instead of doing
on premise deployment,

457
00:19:30,710 --> 00:19:34,280
we took all those servers and
put them in a big data center

458
00:19:34,280 --> 00:19:37,160
somewhere else, and we
just connect to that.

459
00:19:37,160 --> 00:19:39,777
And we share that with a bunch
of other people too, right.

460
00:19:39,777 --> 00:19:41,360
We share that with
every other company

461
00:19:41,360 --> 00:19:43,460
that needs resources,
needs Cloud resources

462
00:19:43,460 --> 00:19:45,270
or needs servers.

463
00:19:45,270 --> 00:19:47,630
And this is why I wanted
to explain it this way,

464
00:19:47,630 --> 00:19:52,280
is just to clarify that
the Cloud as we discuss it

465
00:19:52,280 --> 00:19:54,950
can seem kind of like
this ephemeral thing.

466
00:19:54,950 --> 00:19:57,680
But really all we're saying
when we talk about the Cloud

467
00:19:57,680 --> 00:20:00,780
is a bunch of servers
connected to the internet.

468
00:20:00,780 --> 00:20:02,720
We can connect to those
servers because we

469
00:20:02,720 --> 00:20:05,330
have an internet connection,
and so therefore, we

470
00:20:05,330 --> 00:20:07,040
have access to the Cloud.

471
00:20:07,040 --> 00:20:11,010
That's all it is at its core--
a server in a room somewhere.

472
00:20:11,010 --> 00:20:13,650
And it's just that
it's not on premise.

473
00:20:13,650 --> 00:20:17,360
If that same server
that's stored by Amazon

474
00:20:17,360 --> 00:20:20,000
is instead on our local
site, we wouldn't call it

475
00:20:20,000 --> 00:20:21,000
the Cloud necessarily.

476
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:23,417
You might call it a personal
Cloud or something like that,

477
00:20:23,417 --> 00:20:24,810
if you connect to the internet.

478
00:20:24,810 --> 00:20:29,380
But really, that's the only
thing we're talking about here.

479
00:20:29,380 --> 00:20:33,280
And you also see that
it's not an either/or.

480
00:20:33,280 --> 00:20:35,920
We talked about on
premise deployment,

481
00:20:35,920 --> 00:20:38,330
that's getting this
private Cloud idea.

482
00:20:38,330 --> 00:20:42,340
You could have an entirely
Cloud-based platform,

483
00:20:42,340 --> 00:20:44,630
and then yeah, you're
just a Cloud company.

484
00:20:44,630 --> 00:20:47,080
But in reality,
most organizations

485
00:20:47,080 --> 00:20:48,730
are in this kind
of hybrid approach

486
00:20:48,730 --> 00:20:50,660
where some things
are in the Cloud,

487
00:20:50,660 --> 00:20:52,040
some things are on premise.

488
00:20:52,040 --> 00:20:54,290
You that's how we
work Carvana as well.

489
00:20:54,290 --> 00:20:56,920
We still maintain
on premise servers

490
00:20:56,920 --> 00:20:59,470
for a variety of
reasons and use cases,

491
00:20:59,470 --> 00:21:03,226
and we also had our
remote resources.

492
00:21:07,072 --> 00:21:08,530
I won't spend too
much time on this

493
00:21:08,530 --> 00:21:11,113
because we're going to have a
whole lecture around this topic,

494
00:21:11,113 --> 00:21:12,910
but I also just
wanted to highlight

495
00:21:12,910 --> 00:21:15,580
that the way I've been
describing it kind of

496
00:21:15,580 --> 00:21:18,430
falls into this bucket of what
is often called infrastructure

497
00:21:18,430 --> 00:21:19,930
as a service.

498
00:21:19,930 --> 00:21:21,610
This is where we just
treat it as like,

499
00:21:21,610 --> 00:21:23,530
there's a computer in the Cloud.

500
00:21:23,530 --> 00:21:25,400
But in reality,
there's a gradient.

501
00:21:25,400 --> 00:21:27,950
We could be leveraging
Cloud resources just to say,

502
00:21:27,950 --> 00:21:31,490
I need access to computer
or storage in the Cloud.

503
00:21:31,490 --> 00:21:33,490
But we could also say,
hey, actually what

504
00:21:33,490 --> 00:21:36,640
I want is a platform
that allows me to build

505
00:21:36,640 --> 00:21:40,690
my resources on Cloud,
on a Cloud platform,

506
00:21:40,690 --> 00:21:43,630
but I'm not actually managing
the underlying computers.

507
00:21:43,630 --> 00:21:45,890
Or take that to
the other extreme,

508
00:21:45,890 --> 00:21:48,400
and then we could look at
software as a service, where

509
00:21:48,400 --> 00:21:50,650
that's just saying, hey, we
have basically no control

510
00:21:50,650 --> 00:21:51,910
over the resources.

511
00:21:51,910 --> 00:21:53,540
Think about something
like Google Docs.

512
00:21:53,540 --> 00:21:55,340
That is a software as a service.

513
00:21:55,340 --> 00:21:57,500
It is a Cloud resource, right.

514
00:21:57,500 --> 00:22:00,740
I can connect to it, I can
edit my document remotely,

515
00:22:00,740 --> 00:22:03,640
but it is entirely in the Cloud.

516
00:22:03,640 --> 00:22:08,050
And also, I'm not interacting
with the underlying compute

517
00:22:08,050 --> 00:22:08,796
resources.

518
00:22:11,880 --> 00:22:14,530
So again, there are some real
benefits to Cloud computing.

519
00:22:14,530 --> 00:22:19,530
Basically, take all those cons
of on premise resources and you

520
00:22:19,530 --> 00:22:22,980
have all the pros
of Cloud resources.

521
00:22:22,980 --> 00:22:24,310
I pulled out this example here.

522
00:22:24,310 --> 00:22:25,490
It's an interesting one.

523
00:22:25,490 --> 00:22:28,650
Basically, this was a case
where the New York Times wanted

524
00:22:28,650 --> 00:22:33,630
to basically scan
in all the high--

525
00:22:33,630 --> 00:22:36,840
or do high resolution scans
of all their newspapers from

526
00:22:36,840 --> 00:22:38,530
the 1800s on.

527
00:22:38,530 --> 00:22:42,600
So massive amount of
information, a ton of--

528
00:22:42,600 --> 00:22:44,800
I mean, again, these are
very high resolution scans.

529
00:22:44,800 --> 00:22:47,500
So they're very large
files, and it's every page.

530
00:22:47,500 --> 00:22:52,830
So it was a very compute
intensive process.

531
00:22:52,830 --> 00:22:56,520
The on premise solution would
say, OK, well, have a scanner

532
00:22:56,520 --> 00:23:00,000
here at your desk, run each
of the images through there

533
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:05,020
and then store them, basically,
onto your local computers

534
00:23:05,020 --> 00:23:07,900
in the office, and you
need to have enough storage

535
00:23:07,900 --> 00:23:10,340
on in your office to do that.

536
00:23:10,340 --> 00:23:13,857
And you also only have
one computer to do this.

537
00:23:13,857 --> 00:23:15,440
So you've done all
your scans already,

538
00:23:15,440 --> 00:23:16,483
so that process is done.

539
00:23:16,483 --> 00:23:17,900
That has to happen
no matter what.

540
00:23:17,900 --> 00:23:20,840
But now when you want to process
them, maybe edit the colors,

541
00:23:20,840 --> 00:23:23,470
adjust this and put them
into certain storage system,

542
00:23:23,470 --> 00:23:27,130
that all has to be done
through your computer.

543
00:23:27,130 --> 00:23:29,830
What they did instead was
they leveraged the Cloud.

544
00:23:29,830 --> 00:23:31,780
They said, hey,
well, what we can do

545
00:23:31,780 --> 00:23:35,210
is we can spin up 100 computers,
a hundred virtual computers,

546
00:23:35,210 --> 00:23:37,960
we call them virtual machines,
and they spun up a hundred

547
00:23:37,960 --> 00:23:41,690
of those and did all the
processing in parallel.

548
00:23:41,690 --> 00:23:45,130
So they ran all their-- or
they split up all their files

549
00:23:45,130 --> 00:23:47,650
and said, hey, each of
these 100 virtual machines

550
00:23:47,650 --> 00:23:51,250
will take some chunk
of our repository

551
00:23:51,250 --> 00:23:54,130
here and then push that live
and store it in the Cloud

552
00:23:54,130 --> 00:23:55,280
as well, too.

553
00:23:55,280 --> 00:23:56,800
And that caused them--

554
00:23:56,800 --> 00:23:59,680
I think the estimate was
something like 900 bucks to do.

555
00:23:59,680 --> 00:24:03,330
Took about 24 hours, 900
bucks in Cloud resources,

556
00:24:03,330 --> 00:24:04,500
which is not cheap.

557
00:24:04,500 --> 00:24:08,820
But if you factor in that they
used 100 different computers.

558
00:24:08,820 --> 00:24:12,680
I mean, even if these were 100
pretty cheap computers at $500

559
00:24:12,680 --> 00:24:15,820
a piece, you'd already still
be spending-- what is that?

560
00:24:15,820 --> 00:24:19,650
$50,000 on just computers alone.

561
00:24:19,650 --> 00:24:22,920
So, I mean, it's just
so wildly valuable

562
00:24:22,920 --> 00:24:27,750
to be able to scale up
almost limitless resources.

563
00:24:27,750 --> 00:24:30,870
You're basically trading
off this capital expense,

564
00:24:30,870 --> 00:24:34,680
this upfront cost for
variable expenses.

565
00:24:34,680 --> 00:24:36,460
This might not seem
that powerful yet,

566
00:24:36,460 --> 00:24:41,520
but imagine tomorrow you wanted
to start a company that might--

567
00:24:41,520 --> 00:24:45,490
start a website, let's say, that
might have to scale globally.

568
00:24:45,490 --> 00:24:48,380
If you just bought your own
servers to host that website,

569
00:24:48,380 --> 00:24:51,820
you would have to upfront
buy as big of a computer

570
00:24:51,820 --> 00:24:54,850
as you could afford or as much
as you needed for your user

571
00:24:54,850 --> 00:24:57,970
base, versus with the
Cloud, you would just

572
00:24:57,970 --> 00:25:01,810
purchase the bare minimum for
what you need right now, and as

573
00:25:01,810 --> 00:25:04,120
that user base
increases, it's very easy

574
00:25:04,120 --> 00:25:08,530
to just scale that
up automatically.

575
00:25:08,530 --> 00:25:10,780
That resource pooling
like we talked about

576
00:25:10,780 --> 00:25:13,480
before, where we say,
hey, rather than us having

577
00:25:13,480 --> 00:25:15,730
a bunch of single on premise
servers, every company

578
00:25:15,730 --> 00:25:17,870
having their own
on premise servers,

579
00:25:17,870 --> 00:25:21,430
we pool all these resources
into a few big Cloud providers,

580
00:25:21,430 --> 00:25:24,280
and now their goal
is to optimize

581
00:25:24,280 --> 00:25:25,632
the utilization of this.

582
00:25:25,632 --> 00:25:28,090
They don't want to have a bunch
of unused resources sitting

583
00:25:28,090 --> 00:25:28,700
around.

584
00:25:28,700 --> 00:25:31,557
So if I've rented 100
computers to use for 24 hours,

585
00:25:31,557 --> 00:25:33,890
they're going to make sure
that when I'm not using that,

586
00:25:33,890 --> 00:25:35,990
somebody else is using
those compute resources.

587
00:25:35,990 --> 00:25:38,540
So they're going to
maximize availability to me,

588
00:25:38,540 --> 00:25:40,990
but minimize the
unused resources, which

589
00:25:40,990 --> 00:25:44,230
really allows them to
dramatically cut costs on that.

590
00:25:44,230 --> 00:25:46,750
So from my side of
it, it's really nice.

591
00:25:46,750 --> 00:25:50,300
No matter what task I have to
do from a compute perspective,

592
00:25:50,300 --> 00:25:52,172
I just assume I have
infinite resource.

593
00:25:52,172 --> 00:25:54,130
I assume I have infinite
computers, or at least

594
00:25:54,130 --> 00:25:59,060
as much as I can afford, because
I can just, one button click,

595
00:25:59,060 --> 00:26:02,680
spin up a massive computer or
dozens of massive computers

596
00:26:02,680 --> 00:26:03,560
using the Cloud.

597
00:26:03,560 --> 00:26:06,200
So it's a lot of power.

598
00:26:06,200 --> 00:26:07,920
Great power, great
responsibility, right?

599
00:26:07,920 --> 00:26:10,920
So we will be intentional on
how we utilize and manage that,

600
00:26:10,920 --> 00:26:12,630
though.

601
00:26:12,630 --> 00:26:15,600
It's on demand and
self-service, so we

602
00:26:15,600 --> 00:26:17,020
are the ones in charge of that.

603
00:26:17,020 --> 00:26:20,880
We say, hey, I want to spin
up these computers now,

604
00:26:20,880 --> 00:26:22,030
I get to click the buttons.

605
00:26:22,030 --> 00:26:24,630
I don't have to call somebody
and wait for this to happen.

606
00:26:24,630 --> 00:26:28,480
I can just manage, spin up, spin
down, keep track of the usage,

607
00:26:28,480 --> 00:26:30,860
all that sort of stuff myself.

608
00:26:30,860 --> 00:26:34,340
I don't have to worry
about maintenance at all.

609
00:26:34,340 --> 00:26:36,900
If there are some machines
that are going bad,

610
00:26:36,900 --> 00:26:37,970
they swap them out.

611
00:26:37,970 --> 00:26:40,700
I don't notice that if
I'm leveraging these Cloud

612
00:26:40,700 --> 00:26:41,790
resources.

613
00:26:41,790 --> 00:26:44,465
We'll also talk about
the security value

614
00:26:44,465 --> 00:26:46,340
that comes with that,
and that they duplicate

615
00:26:46,340 --> 00:26:48,000
across multiple locations.

616
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:50,570
So even if there's an
earthquake in one area,

617
00:26:50,570 --> 00:26:53,090
my information can be
duplicated across so many areas

618
00:26:53,090 --> 00:26:55,990
that I'm never going
to notice that issue.

619
00:26:55,990 --> 00:26:57,880
It's completely automatic.

620
00:26:57,880 --> 00:27:01,990
So again, I can have a business
that maybe all of a sudden

621
00:27:01,990 --> 00:27:04,670
sees some massive spike
in growth overnight.

622
00:27:04,670 --> 00:27:08,020
I can set up my services
or my servers in the Cloud,

623
00:27:08,020 --> 00:27:10,100
such that they automatically
adjust to that.

624
00:27:10,100 --> 00:27:13,130
So as long as it stays
below what I can afford,

625
00:27:13,130 --> 00:27:16,850
I can scale up to any number of
users basically instantaneously,

626
00:27:16,850 --> 00:27:18,910
and I can do this
globally, because there

627
00:27:18,910 --> 00:27:23,780
are data centers on every corner
of this globe pretty much now.

628
00:27:23,780 --> 00:27:27,720
And all that leads to it being
just a very economical solution.

629
00:27:27,720 --> 00:27:30,920
You're only paying
for what you need.

630
00:27:30,920 --> 00:27:33,680
That's not a complete
solution, there are still

631
00:27:33,680 --> 00:27:37,110
issues with that, and we'll talk
about some of these challenges,

632
00:27:37,110 --> 00:27:40,810
but broadly speaking, a
ton of benefits associated.

633
00:27:40,810 --> 00:27:44,260
But in the same breath, while
I say they are very secure,

634
00:27:44,260 --> 00:27:46,630
that security also means that--

635
00:27:46,630 --> 00:27:49,478
or from a consolidation
standpoint,

636
00:27:49,478 --> 00:27:51,520
that also means there is
a security vulnerability

637
00:27:51,520 --> 00:27:55,330
in that all of our
resources are isolated

638
00:27:55,330 --> 00:27:59,950
to one place in the Cloud, or
all to one set of resources.

639
00:27:59,950 --> 00:28:02,410
If my company is
leveraging AWS, which

640
00:28:02,410 --> 00:28:05,110
we're going to use in this
class, Amazon Web Services,

641
00:28:05,110 --> 00:28:08,800
if I have admin privileges to my
users-- or my company's account

642
00:28:08,800 --> 00:28:12,290
and I lose my password or
somebody gets my password,

643
00:28:12,290 --> 00:28:14,830
they could technically take
down our whole business.

644
00:28:14,830 --> 00:28:18,100
So there are some really
intentional security steps

645
00:28:18,100 --> 00:28:21,530
we need to take to make sure
that our platform stays secure,

646
00:28:21,530 --> 00:28:23,870
because now we've kind of
consolidated all to one thing,

647
00:28:23,870 --> 00:28:24,370
right.

648
00:28:24,370 --> 00:28:26,690
It's not just a bunch of
servers sitting in our office,

649
00:28:26,690 --> 00:28:31,030
it's a single website
you have to log into.

650
00:28:31,030 --> 00:28:33,310
Similarly, and again,
I'll preface this

651
00:28:33,310 --> 00:28:37,620
and say that these
platforms are very secure.

652
00:28:37,620 --> 00:28:41,730
They heavily focus on ensuring
privacy and reliability

653
00:28:41,730 --> 00:28:42,880
of the platform.

654
00:28:42,880 --> 00:28:47,550
There is still a risk in that
we are transferring information

655
00:28:47,550 --> 00:28:53,040
over the internet and it's being
stored in a Cloud repository,

656
00:28:53,040 --> 00:28:54,850
as compared to as
we talked about,

657
00:28:54,850 --> 00:28:57,630
an air gapped thing where we
have a server in an isolated

658
00:28:57,630 --> 00:29:01,260
room, locked room, no windows,
no connection to the internet.

659
00:29:01,260 --> 00:29:03,950
It will never match
that level of security.

660
00:29:03,950 --> 00:29:09,210
So again, there is some
trade off a bit with that.

661
00:29:09,210 --> 00:29:11,460
And we've seen
this as well, too,

662
00:29:11,460 --> 00:29:14,850
that there have been
massive outages and breaches

663
00:29:14,850 --> 00:29:16,175
of these Cloud platforms.

664
00:29:16,175 --> 00:29:17,550
But you've probably
noticed this,

665
00:29:17,550 --> 00:29:20,610
days when you get on the
internet or open up your phone

666
00:29:20,610 --> 00:29:23,923
and like, 35% of your apps
don't work for whatever reason,

667
00:29:23,923 --> 00:29:26,340
that's probably because there
was some major outage on one

668
00:29:26,340 --> 00:29:28,440
of these large Cloud
providers that took out

669
00:29:28,440 --> 00:29:29,790
a good chunk of the internet.

670
00:29:29,790 --> 00:29:33,436
So that can happen, but
again, rare occurrences.

671
00:29:36,080 --> 00:29:40,000
And also while I said that
these platforms are economical,

672
00:29:40,000 --> 00:29:45,023
this cost, again,
if you have very--

673
00:29:45,023 --> 00:29:47,190
and this is some of these
articles are talking about

674
00:29:47,190 --> 00:29:50,440
is an example of one company
that chose to leave the Cloud,

675
00:29:50,440 --> 00:29:52,690
and we'll talk about this
more later on this semester.

676
00:29:52,690 --> 00:29:56,010
But for them, their
argument was basically

677
00:29:56,010 --> 00:30:02,910
we understand how many users we
have, we don't expect growth,

678
00:30:02,910 --> 00:30:05,410
we have very predictable
growth in our business.

679
00:30:05,410 --> 00:30:09,840
And so we'd rather actually
trade off those fixed costs,

680
00:30:09,840 --> 00:30:10,800
the variable costs.

681
00:30:10,800 --> 00:30:16,350
There is variation in pricing
on platforms like AWS.

682
00:30:16,350 --> 00:30:19,710
And so instead, if
they just purchase

683
00:30:19,710 --> 00:30:22,050
some cheap resources, some
cheap servers themselves,

684
00:30:22,050 --> 00:30:25,950
manage and maintain them,
it can reduce costs overall.

685
00:30:25,950 --> 00:30:30,030
So it really is a question of
not necessarily is it cheaper

686
00:30:30,030 --> 00:30:31,900
to be on premise
or in the Cloud,

687
00:30:31,900 --> 00:30:34,170
it's more a question of
where your business is at

688
00:30:34,170 --> 00:30:36,950
and how you all
operate, which platform

689
00:30:36,950 --> 00:30:41,100
or which approach is
the most valuable.

690
00:30:41,100 --> 00:30:44,770
And this is related to
that, it is to say like,

691
00:30:44,770 --> 00:30:48,350
once you've put all your
resources in the Cloud,

692
00:30:48,350 --> 00:30:50,170
especially consolidated to--

693
00:30:50,170 --> 00:30:52,780
and you usually benefit from
consolidating to a single vendor

694
00:30:52,780 --> 00:30:54,980
like AWS or Google.

695
00:30:54,980 --> 00:30:57,880
Once you've centralized all
to AWS or all to Google,

696
00:30:57,880 --> 00:30:59,840
it's really hard to
switch out of that.

697
00:30:59,840 --> 00:31:00,850
It's really hard to
say, well, now I'm

698
00:31:00,850 --> 00:31:02,808
going to actually migrate
to a cheaper solution

699
00:31:02,808 --> 00:31:05,050
or I'm going to migrate on
premise, because there's

700
00:31:05,050 --> 00:31:08,980
just so much effort in standing
those up and spending those down

701
00:31:08,980 --> 00:31:11,270
that typically once
you get bought in,

702
00:31:11,270 --> 00:31:14,270
it's rare that people want
to leave these platforms.

703
00:31:14,270 --> 00:31:17,650
So it's something to
consider as you're

704
00:31:17,650 --> 00:31:20,570
leveraging any of these tools.

705
00:31:20,570 --> 00:31:22,200
And finally-- I think
this last point.

706
00:31:22,200 --> 00:31:27,930
Yeah, this is one where it's
kind of a pro and con as well.

707
00:31:27,930 --> 00:31:31,470
All these are gray areas.

708
00:31:31,470 --> 00:31:34,920
I mean, by its nature, one of
the values of taking this course

709
00:31:34,920 --> 00:31:38,580
and pursuing an understanding
in Cloud computing

710
00:31:38,580 --> 00:31:41,940
is to gain certifications and
new employment opportunities

711
00:31:41,940 --> 00:31:43,010
in the Cloud.

712
00:31:43,010 --> 00:31:45,300
So from an individual
standpoint,

713
00:31:45,300 --> 00:31:47,460
learning about the Cloud
and leveraging the Cloud

714
00:31:47,460 --> 00:31:49,840
can be really valuable, from
a job security standpoint.

715
00:31:49,840 --> 00:31:53,640
All of these badges here, these
are different certifications

716
00:31:53,640 --> 00:31:55,560
you can get through AWS.

717
00:31:55,560 --> 00:31:58,580
There's probably even more today
than when I pulled this image.

718
00:31:58,580 --> 00:32:00,240
They're constantly
adding new things.

719
00:32:00,240 --> 00:32:03,760
And these are really
awesome things to pursue.

720
00:32:03,760 --> 00:32:05,970
They're not easy-- in
this class, for context,

721
00:32:05,970 --> 00:32:08,280
it's kind of sitting at this
Cloud practitioner level.

722
00:32:08,280 --> 00:32:10,225
You won't have all
of the knowledge

723
00:32:10,225 --> 00:32:11,850
necessary to take
this exam, but you'll

724
00:32:11,850 --> 00:32:14,977
have quite a bit of the
base knowledge for it.

725
00:32:14,977 --> 00:32:16,810
A little bit of effort
and studying outside,

726
00:32:16,810 --> 00:32:18,780
which you can reach out
to me if you want to,

727
00:32:18,780 --> 00:32:21,097
have some more research on
that, resources on that.

728
00:32:21,097 --> 00:32:23,680
But a little bit of study and
you should be able to take that.

729
00:32:23,680 --> 00:32:26,602
And once you've taken the
Cloud practitioner exam,

730
00:32:26,602 --> 00:32:28,560
then you can move on to
some of these associate

731
00:32:28,560 --> 00:32:30,750
and then professional exams.

732
00:32:30,750 --> 00:32:32,430
But either way, it's
all to say that one

733
00:32:32,430 --> 00:32:35,760
of the promises of the
Cloud was that it was going

734
00:32:35,760 --> 00:32:38,572
to reduce the need,
